<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900822-0049</DOCNO><DOCID>900822-0049.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Control Data Corp.:   Approval Received to Sell   Mainframes to Soviet Union</HL><DATE>08/22/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   CDA FREST</CO><IN>MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><GV>COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)</GV><LP>   Control Data Corp. said the Commerce Department granted anexport license to ship six of the company's largest computersto the Soviet Union, where they will monitor nuclear powerplant performance.   The Cyber 960 mainframe machines made by theMinneapolis-based manufacturer are valued at a total of $32million and are believed the most powerful exported to theU.S.S.R. Shipment will begin next month, Control Data said.</LP><TEXT>   Ordered after the disaster at the Soviets' Chernobylreactor, the computers will analyze safety factors atcivilian power-generating plants. The export license followedassurances that the computers would be limited to safetyanalysis.</TEXT></DOC>